04437nam a22006255i 9781487518004DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875180047 a10.3138/97814875180042doi  a(DE-B1597)540139  a(OCoLC)1138500567  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPER0040002bisacsh1 aBrook, Clodagh J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScreening Religions in Italy :bContemporary Italian Cinema and Television in the Post-secular Public Sphere /cClodagh J. Brook. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Italy, Secularization, and the Post-Secular -- t1. The Space for Religious Filmmaking: Policy and Infrastructures -- t2. The Persistence of Religion on Screen: Icons, Rituals, and the Arts -- t3. Countercultural Catholic Values in the Public Sphere -- t4. Protest in the Public Sphere: The Shifting Line between Religious and Secular Space -- t5. Voicing the Religious Other: Assimilation, Horror, Resolution -- tConclusion: Seeing Is Believing – Italian Filmmaking Looks Post-Secularism in the Eye -- tReferences -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion has had been foundational in shaping Italy. Home to the Vatican State, the Italian peninsula is the religious centre for one billion Catholics globally. It is also increasingly home to those of other faiths, especially Islam. Italy’s development as a contemporary post-secular and multi-religious society is fraught and fascinating. The recent return of religious discourse from the margins of Western society to a central position is a sign of what German philosopher, Jürgen Habermas, has defined as the post-secular condition. Habermas and others have questioned what most people in the West had, up to a few years ago, taken for granted: the unstoppable forward march of secularization and the subsequent marginalization of religion. Instead, one of the greatest global fault-lines in the contemporary world – the divide between absolutist extremist Islamic faith and liberal, but Christian-inflected, secular values – has religious identity at its core. The first book-length study to examine religion in contemporary Italian cinema and television fiction, Screening Religions in Italy identifies two key issues: how Italian filmmaking constructs the continuing position of religion in the public sphere and why religion persists on Italian screens. It spans genres such as horror, comedy, hagiopics, and TV fiction, and explores both commercial and art-house filmmaking. It treats films and television series that range from Moretti’s Habemus Papam to Sorrentino’s The Young Pope.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMotion pictureszItaly. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aHabermas.  aIslam.  aItalian cinema.  aMoretti.  aSorrentino.  afiction.  ahagiopic.  ahorror.  apost-secular.  areligion.  atelevision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751800440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487518004423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487518004/original  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles